                        <div id="agenda-intro">
                          <h2>Introduction to Agenda</h2>
                          <div class="divide20"></div>
                          <h3>Agenda 1: Kashmir</h3>
                          <p>India is nation which over the years has somewhat developed, if not earned a reputation for featuring various separatist movements. Now there are various links between these movements, from Khalistan to the demand for a united North East, however the oldest and probably the most convoluted of these conflicts is the Kashmir issue. The seeds for the turmoil in Kashmir were first sown in 1947 at the very partition of India with the inclusion of article 370, which granted the area of Kashmir ‘special autonomous statuses. Yes it wouldn't be for another twenty years before the separatists emerged following the 1987 Jammu and Kashmir elections, however I wouldn't limit this conflict to just one between India and Pakistan as China to plays a large role in the region. So I would advise all delegates to prepare wisely.</p>
                          <h3>Agenda 2: Sedition</h3>
                          <p>Section 124-A of the Indian penal code talks about how if somebody is found to be attempting to bring hatred or contempt towards the government of India, he may be imprisoned or fined. Now on a very denotative level, this law seems to against the very ethos of nation which practices the freedom of speech. Such was the nationwide debate which sparked after the recent protests at the Jawaharlal Nehru campus. One way to look at this issue is as stated above. However, the opposing perspective that was professed by the government of India was that the protests were anti-national in nature. Home minister Rajnath Singh informed the public of possible links between the Laskar-e-Taiba and the protests. So the question arises, if the protests really were anti-national, then was the Sedition law relevant? A piece advice I would give to all delegates before the  committee is not to limit ones research just to the JNU crisis, there are other instances where this law has been successful and so are worth looking at.</p>
